JOHANNESBURG – South Africa recorded a trade surplus of R4.56-billion in October following a surplus of R4.48-billion in the previous month, the South African Revenue Service (Sars) said on Thursday. The tax collector said the surplus was a result of export receipts of R104.51-billion against imports of R99.95-billion. READ: SA's current account deficit widens “Exports increased from September 2017 to October 2017 by R2.29-billion (2.2 percent) and imports increased from September 2017 to October 2017 by R2.21billion (2.3 percent),” SARS said. The October trade data leaves South Africa with a trade surplus of nearly R52-billion in the year to date, compared with a shortfall of nearly R10-billion over the same period in 2016. From January to October exports rose 6.6 percent on a year-on-year basis, while imports dipped by 0.2 percent. African News Agency